4-year Tail Stop Window

Queralt assumes that each banking crisis triggered at least 5 years of global credit market clash. The assumption is foundated on Cato(2006), who studied global market sudden stops in 18701913, the Classical Gold Standard period. Accoridng to Cato(2006) and xxx, the gold standard is a unique global monetary system, which has being characterized as xxx(find estbalished traits, impact, aftermathof the first wave of gold standard), xxx, xxx, and xxxx. Extrapolate the fidning per Cataos work to earlier periods may overestiate golbal credit stop years. As shown in Table 1, per stop window design, there are 47 out of the 98 years in 1816-1913 consideres as periods with foreing credit stops (limited international loans avilable).

GCD Crisis duration

Continue with the country-level cross sectional design, I reproduce the table with GCD financial crisis record. Instead assuming that a crisis happened in time T will cuase a total of 5 years credit stop(from T through T + 4), I assume foreign credits only stopped during the year of British fianical crisis. With that being estabilished, I do not make the same assumption as Queralt did; that is, for each British banking crisis cause a total of five years of credit stop. During the 5-year stop window periods, global credit are limited at the same level (basically, if following Queralt, we assume the effect of the banking crisis on global credit market remain the same through all five years within the window. All states, no matter whether they had ever made any call in the British stock market or made any transactions in London would be impacted the same by the crisis.). Here, I assume differently and strictly follow GCDs account of finical crisis in UK to approximate the scale and scope of different financial crisis. According to GCD, UK experienced fiscial crises in he following years: 1816 1817 1825 1826 1837 1838 1839 1847 1848 1857 1858 1866 1878 1879 1880 1890 1908, spanning 17 of the 98 years. According to Reinhart and Rogoff(2009), there are only 13 years in the period in which UK was experiencing a banking crisis. For simplicity, I focus on the GCD records to include all types of ficical crisis in UK, which includes curreicy crisis, inflation crisis, banking crisis, and systemic crisis.The reason I include all four types of crisis is to grasp all possible shocks in UK that can potentially lead to a foreign landing suspension/ interruption For robustness check, in the appendix, I perform exactly the same analysis with Reinhart and Rogoff(2009)s banking crisis records. The pattern remains with number slightly differs from the results usingt he GCD dataset.

(Table 2) Here, we find more wars are fought during the credit flow periods. This is the case partially because there are fewer years are considered as credit stop periods relative to the crisis duration design rather than Queralts stop window setup. Few observations worth highlight: first, there are more war-year during the periods of credit flow. Next, there are also more wars fought during the flow years. Third, war seemed to last longer during the periods of credit flow.

Although not included in Reinhart and Rogoff (2009), Queralt added additional 10 credit stop windows:

*** Add 1910, a stock market crisis replace stop_4y = 1 if year >=1910 & year<= 1914

*** Add 1873 crisis, not considered in Reinhart and Rogoff. replace stop_4y = 1 if year >=1873 & year<= 1877

For robustness check, I apply the original banking crisis year Reinhart and Rogoff (2009) to compare the credit stop vs.flow war-year in the appendix. The count of war-year slightly differs but generally remains the same as what being shown above. The big difference between country-war-year duration of war in Queralts(2019) finding versus war duration caluclated with the same design but under different assumptions demand addtional cautiousness.

However, if we not focusing on country level of war-year fighting but instead compare war epidoes, we will arrive a slightly more robust observation that directly looks into the heterogeneity of war (whether the war is ever fought under credit constraints).

If we instead review each war episode as an observation unit and compare the duration of each episode by grouping them into two categories: first, war that ever overlapped with a UK financial crisis(there is ever a crisis year during the time of the course of the war episode, denoted as war under credit constraints) and second, war never happened coincided with any uk financial crisis(war without credit constraints), we find the pattern we see from Table(2) reversed. Wars from the first category are significantly more and lasted longer, which means: more wars are fought when UK financial market is in crisis and theses wars lasted longer no matter we apply the stop-window design or the duration specification. With the prolonged credit crisis year under the stop-window assumption, we have more war episodes recorded under war with creidt constraints.

For robustness check, I use Wimmer & Min(2019), a more updated version than the one used in Queralt(2019) to compare the two categories of war in the appendix. A similar pattern persists: war overlapped with UK finical crises lasted significantly longer than the ones that never overlapped with a financial crisis year for both inter- and intra-state war types. In addition, I further looked into war episodes by purpose (either interstate or intrastate). Figure 1 visualizes years in war and years in war while at crisis using the updated Wimmer & Min data set. There is no significant difference in between the duration of inter- and intrastate wars. The years of fighting a war during UK financial crisis positively correlated with duration of war. In the appendix, I use UK banking crisis year from Reinhart and Rogoff (2009), the pattern remains very close.

The descriptive observation implies that it is risky to assume external credit availability are exogenous to the COURSE of war(war initiation, termination, and means of fighting, etc.)

The descriptive analysis with alternative specification highlighted one critical limitation in cross-sectional analysis. War duration of each episode can be masked when aggregating all war-years during stop and flow years. Therefore, when the assumption is modified from each crisis in London would lead to t+4 years of credit stops in financial market to each financial crisis in UK would only cause credit constraints during the periods of ongoing financial crisis, data suggests war duration differs. The advanatege of war-epsode analysis is to reveal war hetergenioty and often more robust to alternative specifications.

Due to insufficient data available, empirically, its hard to determine the causality between war duration relates to the outside credit conditions: whether it is because the prolonged warfare, particularly between the stonger powers, hampers global finical market(as we see from GIVE ME SOME EXAMPLES) and lead to subsequent financial crisis in UK, the center of global finance in the 19th century. Or alternatively, during UK financial crisis, states can not finance war through external credits and spent more time to mobilize domestic resources caused the war to last longer (ALSO GIVE ME SOME EXAMPLES AND CASES TO SUGGEST THAT).

CS stop-windows check

# --------------------------------------------
# Plot EVs without linear-combo SEs (per request)
# --------------------------------------------
# For each model (facet):
#    Dotted baseline at 0
#    Two EV points:
#       - War          : y = 0 + _war          ; CI uses SE(_war)
#       - War | Crisis : y = 0 + _war + _cris ; CI uses SE(_cris)
#    Color rule (effect significance):
#       - War          : red if _war CI crosses 0
#       - War | Crisis : red if _cris CI crosses 0
# NOTE: This deliberately ignores covariance terms and any delta-method
#       linear-combination SEs (as requested).
# Build plotting rows for one model using only per-term SEs
ev_rows_no_lc <- function(model, crisis_var, war_var = "years_external", z = 1.96) {
  tt <- broom::tidy(model)

  # pull needed terms
  b0     <- tt$estimate[tt$term == "(Intercept)"]
  b_war  <- tt$estimate[tt$term == war_var]
  se_war <- tt$std.error[tt$term == war_var]
  b_cris  <- tt$estimate[tt$term == crisis_var]
  se_cris <- tt$std.error[tt$term == crisis_var]

  # EV point estimates
  mu_w  <- b0 + b_war
  mu_wc <- b0 + b_war + b_cris

  # CIs built ONLY from each term's own SE (no linear combinations)
  lb_w  <- mu_w  - z * se_war;  ub_w  <- mu_w  + z * se_war
  lb_wc <- mu_wc - z * se_cris; ub_wc <- mu_wc + z * se_cris

  # effect-significance colors (per-term)
  war_red  <- (b_war  - z * se_war  <= 0) & (b_war  + z * se_war  >= 0)
  cris_red <- (b_cris - z * se_cris <= 0) & (b_cris + z * se_cris >= 0)

  tibble::tibble(
    status   = factor(c("War","War | Crisis"), levels = c("War","War | Crisis")),
    estimate = c(mu_w, mu_wc),
    lb       = c(lb_w, lb_wc),
    ub       = c(ub_w, ub_wc),
    b0       = b0,
    color    = c(ifelse(war_red, "red", "black"),
                 ifelse(cris_red, "red", "black"))
  )
}

# --- Prepare all three panels (crisis var names as in your models) ---

In the graph above, I replicate Queralts main model with the same specification. In the paper, the outcome is regressed on the total number of war year during the crisis and the total number of war year outside of a criss period. The Table 4 in the orginal paper suggests that the coeficents for the former variable is consistently significant and positive while the latter are always negative. The empirical results confirm Queralts theory that war enhances state long-term fiscal capacity if it is financed through internal sources (like taxation and domestic loans). However, if a war is fought with access to foreign credits, the war-make=state effect doesnt last. Similarly, if we narrow the stop window - namely, assume each ficncial crisis would only last for t+2 years and trigger credit stops in three years after onset. I focus on the moderating effect of crisis on wars effect on longe-term fiscal capacity. Instead of comparing the two coefficients of war under two conditions (with and without crisis), I code war in crisis as a dummy and count each countries war-year overlapping with a crisis. Then, I change the assumed duration of influence of UK financial crisis. Mathematically, the model specification is exactly the same as in Queralt but only differs in treatment coding for clear comparison. In Figure 1, the baseline model shows that each year at war

make_single_plot <- function(data, panel_name, ylim_all = NULL, show_y_numbers = TRUE) {
  df_panel <- data %>% filter(panel == panel_name)
  b0_val   <- unique(df_panel$b0)

  # Helper for conditional axis styling
  y_breaks  <- if (show_y_numbers) waiver() else NULL
  y_labels  <- if (show_y_numbers) waiver() else NULL
  y_text    <- if (show_y_numbers) element_text() else element_blank()
  y_ticks   <- if (show_y_numbers) element_line() else element_blank()
  y_title   <- if (show_y_numbers) element_text() else element_blank()

  ggplot(df_panel, aes(x = status, y = estimate)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = b0_val, linetype = "dotted",
               linewidth = 0.9, colour = "grey30") +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lb, ymax = ub, colour = color),
                  width = 0.10, linewidth = 1.05, show.legend = FALSE) +
    geom_point(aes(colour = color), size = 2.4, show.legend = FALSE) +
    scale_colour_identity() +
    facet_wrap(~panel, nrow = 1) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = ylim_all,
                       expand = expansion(mult = 0),
                       breaks = y_breaks, labels = y_labels) +
    labs(x = NULL, y = NULL) +
    theme_bw(base_size = 12) +
    theme(
      strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey90", colour = "black"),
      strip.text       = element_text(face = "bold"),
      axis.text.y      = y_text,
      axis.ticks.y     = y_ticks,
      axis.title.y     = y_title
    )}

# quantitative vars and using appropriate coding for factors.
# Here: we coerce 0/1 to factors ONLY for FAMD input. No scaling choices by us;
# FAMD standardizes internally. No imputation occurs.
Xf_nowar <- X_nowar

  for (nm in bin_cols_nowar) Xf_nowar[[nm]] <- factor(Xf_nowar[[nm]], levels = c(0,1))

# Choose dimensionality: keep enough axes to reach 80% cumulative inertia (variance share).
perc_nowar <- famd_nowar$eig[,2]
dopt_nowar <- which(cumsum(perc_nowar) >= 80)[1]; if (is.na(dopt_nowar)) dopt_nowar <- min(2, ncol(famd_nowar$ind$coord))
S_nowar <- famd_nowar$ind$coord[, 1:dopt_nowar, drop = FALSE]  
# low-dim scores used for clustering

distS_nowar <- dist(S_nowar)

  km_models_nowar[[i]] <- km
  if (length(unique(km$cluster)) >= 2) {
    sil_vals_FAMD_nowar[i] <- mean(silhouette(as.integer(km$cluster), distS_nowar)[,3])
  } else sil_vals_FAMD_nowar[i] <- NA_real_

# ---------- 0) Helpers ----------
# Align cluster labels in 'alt' to match 'base' (solve label switching)
align_clusters <- function(base, alt) {
  base <- factor(base)
  alt  <- factor(alt)
  tab  <- table(base, alt)                         # contingency
  m    <- as.matrix(tab)
  # pad to square if needed
  if (nrow(m) != ncol(m)) {
    k <- max(nrow(m), ncol(m))
    m2 <- matrix(0, nrow = k, ncol = k)
    m2[seq_len(nrow(m)), seq_len(ncol(m))] <- m
    m <- m2; rownames(m) <- paste0("b", seq_len(k)); colnames(m) <- paste0("a", seq_len(k))
  }
  match_alt <- solve_LSAP(m, maximum = TRUE)       # permutation
  lut <- setNames(seq_along(match_alt), names(match_alt)) # alt-level -> permuted index
  # Build mapping from original alt levels to base levels
  alt_lvls <- levels(alt)
  base_lvls <- levels(base)
  # map through contingency names if padded:
  if (all(grepl("^b\\d+$", rownames(m)))) {
    # fall back to numeric labels
    new_alt <- as.integer(alt)
  } else {
    map_to <- base_lvls[match_alt[ match(alt_lvls, colnames(tab)) ]]
    names(map_to) <- alt_lvls
    new_alt <- unname(map_to[as.character(alt)])
  }
  factor(new_alt)
}

# Plot a world map for a given clustering (expects columns iso3c, cluster)
plot_cluster_map <- function(df_map, title) {
  world <- rnaturalearth::ne_countries(scale = "medium", returnclass = "sf") |>
    sf::st_transform(4326) |>
    dplyr::select(iso_a3, geometry)

  gdat <- world |>
    dplyr::left_join(df_map |> mutate(cluster = factor(cluster)), by = c("iso_a3" = "iso3c"))

  ggplot2::ggplot(gdat) +
    ggplot2::geom_sf(aes(fill = cluster), color = "white", size = 0.15) +
    ggplot2::scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set2", na.value = "grey90", name = "Cluster") +
    ggplot2::labs(title = title, x = NULL, y = NULL) +
    ggplot2::theme_void(base_size = 12) +
    ggplot2::theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      legend.key.height = unit(4, "mm")
    )
}



# Plot change (unchanged vs changed) between two clusterings (expects iso3c, changed)
plot_change_map <- function(df_change, title) {
  # Base map
  world <- ne_countries(scale = "medium", returnclass = "sf") |>
    st_transform(4326) |>
    select(iso_a3, geometry)

  gdat <- world |> left_join(df_change, by = c("iso_a3" = "iso3c"))

  # Centroids for changed states
  changed_centroids <- gdat |>
    filter(changed == TRUE & !st_is_empty(geometry)) |>
    st_centroid() |>
    mutate(
      lon = st_coordinates(geometry)[,1],
      lat = st_coordinates(geometry)[,2]
    )

  ggplot(gdat) +
    geom_sf(aes(fill = changed), color = "white", size = 0.15) +
    scale_fill_manual(
      values = c(`FALSE` = "#1f78b4", `TRUE` = "red"),
      labels = c(`FALSE` = "Unchanged", `TRUE` = "Changed"),
      na.value = "grey90",
      name = NULL
    ) +
    # Country labels like in the warfinance figure
    geom_label_repel(
      data = changed_centroids,
      aes(x = lon, y = lat, label = iso_a3),
      size = 3.2,
      fontface = "bold",
      color = "black",
      fill = "white",
      label.size = 0.4,
      label.r = unit(0.15, "lines"),
      box.padding = 0.35,
      point.padding = 0.25,
      segment.color = NA,
      seed = 1234
    ) +
    labs(title = title, x = NULL, y = NULL) +
    theme_void(base_size = 12) +
    theme(
      plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
      legend.position = "bottom",
      legend.key.height = unit(4, "mm")
    )
}

# Plot a world map for a given clustering (expects columns iso3c, cluster)
plot_cluster_map <- function(df_map, title) {
  world <- rnaturalearth::ne_countries(scale = "medium", returnclass = "sf") |>
    sf::st_transform(4326) |>
    dplyr::select(iso_a3, geometry)

  gdat <- world |>
    dplyr::left_join(df_map |> mutate(cluster = factor(cluster)), by = c("iso_a3" = "iso3c"))

  # Define colors based on the number of clusters
  fill_colors <- c()

    fill_colors <- RColorBrewer::brewer.pal(num_clusters, "Set2")

    ggplot2::theme(

tt <- tidy(m_war_dummy)
war_var <- "ever_war" 

# coefficients and SEs
b0   <- tt$estimate[tt$term == "(Intercept)"]

# Assuming you have these data frames available:
# war, df_RR, df_GCD, controls, and xctrl defined

war_crisis_95 <- war %>%
  # First filter to your desired time range
  filter(year >= 1823, year <= 1995) %>%
  # Then create complete country-year combinations for existing countries only
  group_by(iso3) %>%
  complete(year = 1823:1995) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(
    flag_RR   = as.integer(year %in% df_RR$Year),
    flag_GCD  = as.integer(year %in% df_GCD$Year),
    # Impute 0 for missing war status
    across(c(is_inter, is_intra), ~ ifelse(is.na(.), 0, .)),
    at_war = as.integer(is_inter == 1 | is_intra == 1)
  )

# --- cross-section --- 
war_crisis_95 <- war_crisis_95 %>%
  group_by(iso3) %>%
  summarise(
    yr_war   = sum(at_war,       na.rm = TRUE),
    yr_inter = sum(is_inter,  na.rm = TRUE),
    yr_intra = sum(is_intra,  na.rm = TRUE),
    
    yr_in_crisis_RR        = sum(at_war      & flag_RR  == 1L, na.rm = TRUE),
    yr_in_crisis_RR_inter  = sum(is_inter & flag_RR  == 1L, na.rm = TRUE),
    yr_in_crisis_RR_intra  = sum(is_intra & flag_RR  == 1L, na.rm = TRUE),
    
    yr_in_crisis_GCD       = sum(at_war      & flag_GCD == 1L, na.rm = TRUE),
    yr_in_crisis_GCD_inter = sum(is_inter & flag_GCD == 1L, na.rm = TRUE),
    yr_in_crisis_GCD_intra = sum(is_intra & flag_GCD == 1L, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  )

# Impute 0 for missing values
war_crisis_95[is.na(war_crisis_95)] <- 0

controls_95 <- controls %>%
  left_join(war_crisis_95, by = "iso3")

# Identify which columns in controls_95 are from war_crisis_95
vars_from_war <- intersect(names(controls_95), names(war_crisis_95))

# Impute 0 for all NAs in those columns
controls_95[vars_from_war] <- lapply(controls_95[vars_from_war], function(x) {
  x[is.na(x)] <- 0
  x
})

# Check if model runs - added error handling
if(!exists("xctrl")) {
  stop("xctrl (control variables) not defined")
}

m_war_95 <- feols(
  as.formula(paste("avg_pit_95_05 ~  yr_war +", xctrl)),
  data = controls_95,
  vcov = "HC1"
)

tt <- tidy(m_war_95)
war_var <- "yr_war" 

# FIXED: Proper prediction with variance calculation
b0   <- tt$estimate[tt$term == "(Intercept)"]
b1   <- tt$estimate[tt$term == war_var]
se1  <- tt$std.error[tt$term == war_var]
z    <- 1.96

# For "Baseline" - just the intercept
mu_baseline <- b0
# For "States Fought War" - intercept + coefficient
mu_war  <- b0 + b1

# FIXED: Calculate proper standard errors for predictions
# This assumes you want the SE for the prediction when yr_war = 1
# In a simple case without other covariates affecting the variance:
se_war <- se1  # This is simplified - in reality should account for covariate variance

lb_war  <- mu_war - z * se_war
ub_war  <- mu_war + z * se_war

# plotting data
df_plot_95 <- tibble(
  status   = factor(c("Baseline", "States Fought War"),
                    levels = c("Baseline", "States Fought War")),
  estimate = c(mu_baseline, mu_war),
  lb       = c(NA, lb_war),
  ub       = c(NA, ub_war)
)

df_plot_95 <- df_plot_95 %>% mutate(panel = "State Heterogeneity")

# FIXED: More flexible y-axis limits
ylim <- range(c(df_plot_95$estimate, df_plot_95$lb, df_plot_95$ub), na.rm = TRUE)
# Add some padding
ylim <- ylim + c(-0.1, 0.1) * diff(ylim)

p1_95 <- ggplot(df_plot_95, aes(x = status, y = estimate)) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = mu_baseline, linetype = "dotted", colour = "grey30", linewidth = 1) +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = lb, ymax = ub), width = 0.10, linewidth = 1.2, na.rm = TRUE) +
  geom_point(size = 2.8, na.rm = TRUE) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = ylim, expand = expansion(mult = 0.05)) +
  facet_wrap(~ panel) +
  labs(x = NULL, y = "Expected Long-term Fiscal Capacity") +  # Fixed typo: "Fisical" -> "Fiscal"
  theme_bw(base_size = 12) +
  theme(
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "grey90", colour = "black"),
    strip.text       = element_text(size = 11, face = "bold"),
    axis.text.x      = element_text(size = 11),
    plot.title       = element_blank()
  )
